EVERYONE NEEDS TO USE ENCRYPTION THESE DAYS. You're ISP wont be able to see what you're transferring however downloaders will see you if you're not behind a proxy. AFAIK it is illegal for the RIAA/MPAA etc to bring a law suit against you by breaking the law themselves. Meaning the only way they could see what you're doing is to join in on the torrent. Normally they would get your ISP records after finding you trading and use that as a record for your case. But if its "encrypted" they in theory, cant.

how do you go about encrypting?
In uTorrent, you can turn on encryption by going to options > preferences (Ctrl+P) > BitTorrent > Outgoing: Enforced, Do not allow legacy connections.

zz1zz: Encryption defends you only against your ISP watching what you download/upload.
PeerGuardian (with the only working for me list: http___list_iblocklist_com_?list=bt_level1) defends you against antiP2P organizations by blocking connections to their IPs.
Of course nothing is 100% sure. But the above mentioned steps are better than nothing.
In my country only uploading is illegal, so for those only downloading a safe solution is to use forums with links to sites like rap1dshare.
To upload, or use BitTorrent, I think quite a safe solution is to use a proxy, which is encrypted, doesn't keep logs and of course offers good speed. It's not free, though.
